## Backend Architecture (Minimal Engineering)

### What AAP Needs to Build:

#### 1. AI Endpoint Configuration Storage
- Store per-template or global AI config
- Support OpenAI-compatible API standard
- Secure credential storage (like existing AAP credentials)

#### 2. Failure Context Collector
When job fails, gather:
- Task name, module, error message
- Host facts (OS, version)
- Relevant inventory variables
- Last N lines of stdout/stderr
- Format as structured prompt

#### 3. AI API Client
- POST to configured AI endpoint
- Handle OpenAI-compatible /v1/chat/completions
- Timeout/retry logic
- Parse response

#### 4. Insights Display Engine
- Render AI response in job output UI
- Store insights in job metadata
- Make searchable/filterable

#### 5. Optional: Auto-Remediation Generator
If AI returns playbook YAML in response:
- Create new job template with:
  - Name: "Fix: [original template] - [issue]"
  - Playbook: AI-generated content
  - Same inventory/credentials
  - Tag as "AI-Generated Remediation"

## Example User Workflow

### Scenario: User Creates Job Template

1. User creates "Deploy Web App" job template
2. User checks ✅ Enable AI Insights
3. User configures AI endpoint (or uses org-level default)
4. User runs job → fails on "Install Apache"
5. AAP automatically:
   - Captures failure context
   - Sends to AI endpoint
   - Gets back: "Apache package name is httpd not apache2 on RHEL"
   - Displays insights in job output
   - Optionally creates remediation template
6. User sees:
   - **Option A:** Insights in AAP UI → manually fix playbook
   - **Option B:** Click "Generate Fix Template" → review AI playbook → run it
   - **Option C:** ServiceNow ticket auto-created with insights

## Why This Approach Wins

### ✅ Minimal Architectural Overhead
- No new services (EDA, message bus, observability)
- Leverage existing AAP job execution engine
- Uses existing credential/API framework

### ✅ Customer Brings Their Own AI
Not locked to Red Hat AI or Lightspeed. Support any OpenAI-compatible endpoint:
- Customer's on-prem LLM (vLLM, Ollama, Red Hat AI)
- Azure OpenAI
- AWS Bedrock (with adapter)
- OpenAI directly

### ✅ Incremental Adoption
- Enable per job template (not all-or-nothing)
- Start with high-value/high-failure templates
- Prove ROI before scaling

### ✅ No Playbook Authoring Required
- Users don't write AI integration playbooks
- AAP handles prompt construction automatically
- AI just needs to return structured insights

### ✅ Fits Existing Mental Model
- "Job templates have settings like credentials, surveys, webhooks... now they have AI insights"
- Not a separate "AIOps product" - just a feature

## Phase 1 Deliverables (MVP)

| Component | Effort | Description |
|-----------|--------|-------------|
| UI Checkbox | Low | "Enable AI Insights" in job template settings |
| AI Config Storage | Low | Store endpoint URL, token, model per template or org-level |
| Context Collector | Medium | Gather failure context when job fails |
| AI API Client | Medium | POST to OpenAI-compatible endpoint, parse response |
| Insights Display | Medium | Render AI response in job output UI |
| Documentation | Low | How to configure AI endpoint, example prompts |

**Total Effort:** 1-2 engineers, 2-3 months for MVP

